            <biogHist>
                <p>Donald Macintosh was the son of Angus Macintosh, crofter, and Flora née
                    Macintyre. For the 1841 census Donald and his younger sister Ann (born c. 1834)
                    were living in the household of Angus Macintyre, probably their uncle, and his
                    family, in Bòrnais Ìochdrach. Ten years later Donald Macintosh is recorded as
                    living in Levanach or Baghasdail mu Dheas in the household of Donald Campbell
                    and his two sisters Floraidh and Margaret, working as a tailor. In 1861 he has
                    married Margaret (1838–83), daughter of John Campbell and Mary née MacAskill.
                    They had at least six of a family: Flora (b. 1853), Mary (b. 1855), Angus (b.
                    1857), John (b. 1859), another Angus (b. 1861), and Flora-Ann (b. 1863). In the
                    1881 census John is recorded as a tailor’s apprentice, learning his father’s
                    trade.</p>
                <p>Donald Macintosh’s wife Margaret died of ‘asthma &amp; general debility’ on 17
                    December 1883. In the 1891 census he is recorded as head of household with his
                    daughters Flora and Flora-Ann, the latter of whom speaks English as well as
                    Gaelic – both women gave ‘tailoress’ as their occupation – and a grand-daughter
                    Peggy MacPherson. </p>
                <p>Donald Macintosh died the following year,in July 1892, of acute pneumonia. His
                    son Angus Macintosh witnessed the death certificate. </p>
